The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on shoes
The training rule on standing
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six were standing while giving teachings to people who were sitting. …
“‘I will not give a teaching while standing to anyone sitting who is not sick,’ this is how you should train.”
One should not give a teaching while standing to anyone sitting who is not sick.
If a monk, out of disrespect, gives a teaching while standing to someone sitting who is not sick, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if it is unintentional;
if he is the first offender.
The tenth training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on arms akimbo
The training rule on even levels
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six received almsfood in a heap. …
“‘I will receive an even level of almsfood,’ this is how you should train.”
Almsfood is to be received at an even level.
If a monk, out of disrespect, receives almsfood in a heap, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if it is unintentional;
if he does not know;
if he is insane;
if he is the first offender.
The tenth training rule is finished.
The third sub-chapter on arms akimbo is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on respectfully
The training rule on finding fault
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six were looking at the bowls of others finding fault. …
“‘I will not look at another’s almsbowl finding fault,’ this is how you should train.”
One should not look at the bowl of another finding fault.
If a monk, out of disrespect, looks at the bowl of another finding fault, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if it is unintentional;
if he does not know;
if he looks with the intention of giving or getting someone to give;
if he is not finding fault;
if he is insane;
if he is the first offender.
The eighth training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on shoes
The training rule on headdresses
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six gave teachings to people wearing a headdress. …
“‘I will not give a teaching to anyone wearing a headdress who is not sick,’ this is how you should train.”
A headdress:
if the ends of the hair are not showing it is a headdress.
One should not give a teaching to anyone wearing a headdress who is not sick.
If a monk, out of disrespect, gives a teaching to someone wearing a headdress who is not sick, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if he does not know;
if he teaches the person after getting them to uncover the ends of their hair;
if he is insane;
if he is the first offender.
The sixth training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on mouthfuls
The training rule on scattering rice
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six scattered rice while eating. …
“‘I will not scatter rice while eating,’ this is how you should train.”
One should not scatter rice while eating.
If a monk, out of disrespect, scatters rice while eating, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if he does not know;
if he discards rice while discarding trash;
if he is insane;
if he is the first offender.
The eighth training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on arms akimbo
The training rule on squatting on the heels
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six were squatting on their heels while walking in inhabited areas. …
“‘I will not squat on my heels while walking in inhabited areas,’ this is how you should train.”
One should not squat on one’s heels while walking in an inhabited area.
If a monk, out of disrespect, squats on his heels while walking in an inhabited area, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if it is unintentional;
if he is the first offender.
The fifth training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on respectfully
The training rule on attention on the almsbowl
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six were eating almsfood while looking here and there, and they did not know whether people were still giving or whether they had received too much. …
“‘I will eat almsfood with attention on the almsbowl,’ this is how you should train.”
Almsfood is to be eaten with attention on the bowl.
If a monk, out of disrespect, eats almsfood while looking here and there, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if it is unintentional;
if he is the first offender.
The second training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on arms akimbo
The training rule on arms akimbo
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six were walking in inhabited areas with arms akimbo. …
“‘I will not walk in inhabited areas with arms akimbo,’ this is how you should train.”
One should not walk in an inhabited area with arms akimbo.
If a monk, out of disrespect, walks in an inhabited area with one or both arms akimbo, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if it is unintentional;
if he is the first offender.
The first training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on respectfully
The training rule on in order
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six ate almsfood picking here and there. …
“‘I will eat almsfood in order,’ this is how you should train.”
Almsfood is to be eaten in order.
If a monk, out of disrespect, eats almsfood picking here and there, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if he does not know;
if he picks things out to give to others;
if he picks things out to put it into someone else’s vessel;
if it is a non-bean curry;
if he is insane;
if he is the first offender.
The third training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on evenly all around
The training rule on well-restrained
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six were playing with their hands and feet while walking in inhabited areas. …
“‘I will walk well-restrained in inhabited areas,’ this is how you should train.”
One should be well-restrained while walking in an inhabited area.
If a monk, out of disrespect, plays with his hands and feet while walking in an inhabited area, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if he does not know;
if he is insane;
if he is the first offender.
The fifth training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on laughing loudly
The training rule on swinging the arms
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six were swinging and dangling their arms while walking in inhabited areas. …
“‘I will not swing my arms while walking in inhabited areas,’ this is how you should train.”
One should not swing one’s arms while walking in an inhabited area;
one should walk keeping one’s arms steady.
If a monk, out of disrespect, swings and dangles his arms while walking in an inhabited area, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if it is unintentional;
if he is the first offender.
The seventh training rule is finished.
