The training rule on well-covered
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six were walking in inhabited areas with their bodies uncovered. …
“‘I will walk well-covered in inhabited areas,’ this is how you should train.”
One should be well-covered while walking in an inhabited area.
If a monk, out of disrespect, walks in an inhabited area with his body uncovered, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if he does not know;
if he is insane;
if he is the first offender.
The third training rule is finished.
