The sub-chapter on evenly all around
The training rule on lowered eyes
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six were looking here and there while walking in inhabited areas. …
“‘I will walk with lowered eyes in inhabited areas,’ this is how you should train.”
One should lower one’s eyes while walking in an inhabited area, looking of a plow’s length ahead.
If a monk, out of disrespect, looks here and there while walking in an inhabited area, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if he does not know;
if he is insane;
if he is the first offender.
The seventh training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on mouthfuls
The training rule on shaking the hand
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six ate shaking their hand. …
“‘I will not eat shaking my hand,’ this is how you should train.”
One should not eat shaking one’s hand.
If a monk, out of disrespect, eats shaking his hand, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if he does not know;
if he shakes the hand to discard trash;
if he is insane;
if he is the first offender.
The seventh training rule is finished.
