The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on evenly all around
The training rule on lifted robe
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six were lifting their robe while walking in inhabited areas. …
“‘I will not lift my robe while walking in inhabited areas,’ this is how you should train.”
One should not lift one’s robe while walking in an inhabited area.
If a monk, out of disrespect, lifts his robe on one or both sides while walking in an inhabited area, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if he does not know;
if he is insane;
if he is the first offender.
The ninth training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on shoes
The training rule on vehicles
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six gave teachings to people in vehicles. …
“‘I will not give a teaching to anyone in a vehicle who is not sick,’ this is how you should train.”
a wagon, a carriage, a cart, a chariot, a palanquin, a litter.
One should not give a teaching to anyone in a vehicle who is not sick.
If a monk, out of disrespect, gives a teaching to someone in a vehicle who is not sick, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if it is unintentional;
if he is the first offender.
The third training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on shoes
The training rule on defecating while standing
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six were defecating and urinating while standing. …
“‘When not sick, I will not defecate or urinate while standing,’ this is how you should train.”
If one is not sick, one should not defecate or urinate while standing.
If, out of disrespect, a monk who is not sick defecates or urinates while standing, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if it is unintentional;
if he is the first offender.
The thirteenth training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on slurping
The training rule on holding a staff
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six gave teachings to people holding a staff. …
“‘I will not give a teaching to anyone holding a staff who is not sick,’ this is how you should train.”
a stick measuring 1.6 meters.
What is longer than that is not a staff, nor what is shorter.
One should not give a teaching to anyone holding a staff who is not sick.
If a monk out, of disrespect, gives a teaching to someone holding a staff who is not sick, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if it is unintentional;
if he is the first offender.
The eighth training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on respectfully
The training rule on respectfully
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six were eating almsfood contemptuously, as if not wanting to eat it. …
“‘I will eat almsfood respectfully,’ this is how you should train.”
Almsfood is to be eaten respectfully.
If a monk, out of disrespect, eats almsfood contemptuously, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if he does not know;
if he is insane;
if he is the first offender.
The first training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on arms akimbo
The second training rule on covering the head
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six were covering their heads with their robes while sitting in inhabited areas. …
“‘I will not cover my head while sitting in inhabited areas;’ this is how you should train.”
One should not cover one’s head while sitting in an inhabited area.
If a monk, out of disrespect, covers his head with his upper robe while sitting in an inhabited area, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if he does not know;
if he has entered his dwelling;
if he is insane;
if he is the first offender.
The fourth training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on shoes
The training rule on defecating in water
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six were defecating, urinating, and spitting in water.
People complained and criticized them,
“How can the Sakyan ascetics defecate, urinate, and spit in water? They are just like householders who indulge in worldly pleasures!”
The monks heard the complaints of those people,
and the monks of few desires complained and criticized those monks,
“How can the monks from the group of six do this?” …
“Is it true, monks, that you do this?”
“It’s true, Sir.”
The Buddha rebuked them,
“… Foolish men, how can you do this?
This won’t give rise to confidence in those without it …
And, monks, this training rule should be recited like this:
‘“I will not defecate, urinate, or spit in water,” this is how you should train.’
In this way the Buddha laid down this training rule for the monks.
Soon afterwards, being afraid of wrongdoing, sick monks did not defecate, urinate, or spit in water.
They told the Buddha.
Soon afterwards he gave a teaching and addressed the monks:
“Monks, I allow a sick monk to defecate, urinate, or spit in water.
And so, monks, this training rule should be recited like this:
‘“When not sick, I will not defecate, urinate, or spit in water,” this is how you should train.’
If one is not sick, one should not defecate, urinate, or spit in water.
If, out of disrespect, a monk who is not sick defecates, urinates, or spits in water, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if he does not know;
if he does it on dry ground, but it then spreads to water;
if he is insane;
if he is deranged;
if he is overwhelmed by pain;
if he is the first offender.
The fifteenth training rule is finished.
The seventh sub-chapter on shoes is finished.
“Venerables, the rules to be trained in have been recited.
In regard to this I ask you,
‘Are you pure in this?’
A second time I ask,
‘Are you pure in this?’
A third time I ask,
‘Are you pure in this?’
You are pure in this and therefore silent. I will remember it thus.”
The rules to be trained in are finished.
The chapter on training is finished.
