The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on mouthfuls
The training rule on with a mouthful
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six spoke with food in their mouths. …
“‘I will not speak with food in my mouth,’ this is how you should train.”
One should not speak with food in one’s mouth.
If a monk, out of disrespect, speaks with food in his mouth, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if it is unintentional;
if he is the first offender.
The third training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on slurping
The training rule on containing rice
At one time when the Buddha was staying in the Bhagga country at Susumāragira in the Bhesakaḷā Grove,
the monks in the Kokanada stilt house were discarding their bowl-washing water containing rice in inhabited areas.
People complained and criticized them,
“How can the Sakyan ascetics discard their bowl-washing water containing rice in inhabited areas? They are just like householders who indulge in worldly pleasures!”
The monks heard the complaints of those people,
and the monks of few desires complained and criticized those monks,
“How can those monks do this?” …
“Is it true, monks, that they do this?”
“It’s true, Sir.”
The Buddha criticized them,
“… How can those foolish men do this?
This won’t give rise to confidence in those without it …
And, monks, this training rule should be recited like this:
‘“I will not discard bowl-washing water containing rice in inhabited areas,” this is how you should train.’
One should not discard bowl-washing water containing rice in an inhabited area.
If a monk, out of disrespect, discards bowl-washing water containing rice in an inhabited area, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if he does not know;
if he discards it after removing the rice, after breaking it up, into a receptacle, or after taking it outside;
if he is insane;
if he is the first offender.
The sixth training rule is finished.
