The training rule on swaying the body
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six were swaying and leaning their bodies while walking in inhabited areas. …
“‘I will not sway my body while walking in inhabited areas,’ this is how you should train.”
One should not sway one’s body while walking in an inhabited area;
one should walk keeping one’s body straight.
If a monk, out of disrespect, sways and leans his body while walking in an inhabited area, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if it is unintentional;
if he is the first offender.
The fifth training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on shoes
The training rule on covered heads
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six gave teachings to people with covered heads. …
“‘I will not give a teaching to anyone with a covered head who is not sick,’ this is how you should train.”
With a covered head:
the upper robe also covers the head is what is meant.
One should not give a teaching to anyone with a covered head who is not sick.
If a monk, out of disrespect, gives a teaching to someone with a covered head who is not sick, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if he does not know;
if he teaches the person after getting them to uncover their head;
if he is insane;
if he is the first offender.
The seventh training rule is finished.
