The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on laughing loudly
The training rule on loud noises
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six were noisy while walking in inhabited areas. …
“‘I will not be noisy while walking in inhabited areas,’ this is how you should train.”
One should not be noisy while walking in an inhabited area.
If a monk, out of disrespect, makes loud noises while walking in an inhabited area, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if he does not know;
if he is insane;
if he is the first offender.
The third training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on slurping
The training rule on licking the almsbowl
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six were licking their bowls while eating. …
“‘I will not lick my almsbowl while eating,’ this is how you should train.”
One should not lick one’s bowl while eating.
If a monk, out of disrespect, licks his bowl while eating, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if he does not know;
if only a little food remains and he eats it after collecting it in one place and then licking it;
if he is insane;
if he is the first offender.
The third training rule is finished.
