The sub-chapter on slurping
The training rule on licking the hands
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six were licking their hands while eating. …
“‘I will not lick my hands while eating,’ this is how you should train.”
One should not lick one’s hands while eating.
If a monk, out of disrespect, licks his hands while eating, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if it is unintentional;
if he is the first offender.
The second training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on shoes
The training rule on the ground
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six were sitting on the ground giving teachings to people sitting on seats. …
“‘I will not give a teaching while sitting on the ground to anyone sitting on a seat who is not sick,’ this is how you should train.”
One should not give a teaching while sitting on the ground to anyone sitting on a seat who is not sick.
If a monk, out of disrespect, gives a teaching while sitting on the ground to someone sitting on a seat who is not sick, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if it is unintentional;
if he is the first offender.
The eighth training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on evenly all around
The training rule on evenly all around
Venerables, these rules to be trained in come up for recitation.
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six wore their sarongs hanging down in front and behind.
People complained and criticized them,
“How can the Sakyan ascetics wear their sarongs hanging down in front and behind? They are just like householders who indulge in worldly pleasures!”
The monks heard the complaints of those people,
and the monks of few desires complained and criticized those monks,
“How can the monks from the group of six wear their sarongs hanging down in front and behind?”
After rebuking those monks in many ways, they told the Buddha.
Soon afterwards the Buddha had the Sangha gathered and questioned the monks from the group of six:
“Is it true, monks, that you do this?”
“It’s true, Sir.”
The Buddha rebuked them,
“… Foolish men, how can you do this?
This won’t give rise to confidence in those without it …
And, monks, this training rule should be recited like this:
‘“I will wear my sarong evenly all around,” this is how you should train.’
One should wear one’s sarong evenly all around, covering the navel and the knees.
If a monk, out of disrespect, wears his sarong hanging down in front or behind, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if he does not know;
if he is insane;
if he is the first offender.
The first training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on slurping
The training rule on slurping
At one time the Buddha was staying at Kosambī in Ghosita’s Monastery.
At that time a brahmin had prepared a milk drink for the Sangha.
The monks drank the milk making a slurping sound.
A monk who was previously an entertainer made a joke of it, saying,
“It’s as if the whole sangha were cooled.”
The monks of few desires complained and criticized him,
“How can a monk joke about the Sangha?” …
“Is it true, monk, that you did this?”
“It’s true, Sir.”
The Buddha rebuked him,
“… Foolish man, how can you do this?
This won’t give rise to confidence in those without it …” …
and after rebuking him …
he gave a teaching and addressed the monks:
“Monks, you should not joke about the Buddha, the Teaching, or the Sangha.
If you do, you commit an offense of wrong conduct.”
After rebuking that monk in many ways for being difficult to support … the Buddha said,
“And, monks, this training rule should be recited like this:
‘“I will not slurp while eating,” this is how you should train.’
One should not slurp while eating.
If a monk, out of disrespect, slurps while eating, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if it is unintentional;
if he is the first offender.
The first training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on evenly all around
The second training rule on well-covered
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six were sitting in inhabited areas with their bodies uncovered. …
“‘I will sit well-covered in inhabited areas,’ this is how you should train.”
One should be well-covered while sitting in an inhabited area.
If a monk, out of disrespect, sits in an inhabited area with his body uncovered, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if he does not know;
if he has entered his dwelling;
if he is insane;
if he is the first offender.
The fourth training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on respectfully
The training rule on asking for rice and bean curry
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six ate rice and bean curry that they themselves had asked for.
People complained and criticized them,
“How can the Sakyan ascetics eat rice and bean curry that they themselves have asked for?
Who doesn’t like nice food?
Who doesn’t prefer tasty food?”
The monks heard the complaints of those people,
and the monks of few desires complained and criticized those monks,
“How can the monks from the group of six do this?” …
“Is it true, monks, that you do this?”
“It’s true, Sir.”
The Buddha rebuked them,
“… Foolish men, how can you do this?
This won’t give rise to confidence in those without it …
And, monks, this training rule should be recited like this:
‘“I will not ask for bean curry or rice for myself and then eat it,” this is how you should train.’
In this way the Buddha laid down this training rule for the monks.
Soon afterwards a number of monks were sick.
The monks who were looking after them asked,
“We hope you’re bearing up; we hope you’re getting better?”
“Previously we ate rice and bean curry that we ourselves had asked for, and then we were comfortable.
that the Buddha has prohibited this, we don’t ask because we’re afraid of wrongdoing. And because of that we’re not comfortable.”
They told the Buddha. Soon afterwards he gave a teaching and addressed the monks:
“Monks, I allow a sick monk to eat rice and bean curry that he himself has asked for.
And so, monks, this training rule should be recited like this:
‘“When not sick, I will not ask for bean curry or rice for myself and then eat it,” this is how you should train.’
When one is not sick, one should not ask for bean curry or rice for oneself and then eat it.
If a monk who is not sick, out of disrespect, eats bean curry or rice that he himself has asked for, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if he does not know;
if it is from those who have given an invitation;
if it is for the benefit of someone else;
if it is by means of his own property;
if he is insane;
if he is the first offender.
The seventh training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on shoes
The training rule on shoes
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six gave teachings to people wearing shoes. …
“‘I will not give a teaching to anyone wearing shoes who is not sick,’ this is how you should train.”
One should not give a teaching to anyone wearing shoes who is not sick.
If a monk, out of disrespect, gives a teaching to someone who is not sick and who is standing on shoes, whose shoes are fastened, or whose shoes are loose, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if it is unintentional;
if he is the first offender.
The first training rule is finished.
