The sub-chapter on mouthfuls
The training rule on breaking up balls of food
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six ate breaking up mouthfuls. …
“‘I will not eat breaking up a ball of food,’ this is how you should train.”
One should not eat breaking up balls of food.
If a monk, out of disrespect, eats breaking up balls of food, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if he does not know;
if it is any kind of fruit;
if it is a non-bean curry;
if he is insane;
if he is the first offender.
The fifth training rule is finished.
