The training rule on swaying the head
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six were swaying and hanging their heads while walking in inhabited areas. …
“‘I will not sway my head while walking in inhabited areas,’ this is how you should train.”
One should not sway one’s head while walking in an inhabited area;
one should walk keeping one’s head straight.
If a monk, out of disrespect, sways and hangs his head while walking in an inhabited area, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if it is unintentional;
if he is the first offender.
The ninth training rule is finished.
