Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on respectfully
The training rule on an even measure of bean curry
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six were eating almsfood with large amounts of bean curry. …
“‘I will eat almsfood with the right proportion of bean curry,’ this is how you should train.”
mung-bean curry and black-gram curry.
Almsfood should be eaten with the right proportion of bean curry.
If a monk, out of disrespect, eats much bean curry, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if he does not know;
if it is from those who have given an invitation;
if it is by means of his own property;
if he is insane;
if he is the first offender.
The fourth training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on evenly all around
The second training rule on evenly all around
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six wore their upper robes hanging down in front and behind. …
“‘I will wear my upper robe evenly all around,’ this is how you should train.”
One should wear one’s upper robe evenly all around, making both corners even.
If a monk, out of disrespect, wears his upper robe hanging down in front or behind, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if he does not know;
if he is insane;
if he is the first offender.
The second training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on shoes
The training rule on walking off the path
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six were walking next to the path while giving a teaching to people walking on the path. …
“‘I will not give a teaching while walking next to the path to anyone walking on the path who is not sick,’ this is how you should train.”
One should not give a teaching while walking next to the path to anyone walking on the path who is not sick.
If a monk, out of disrespect, gives a teaching while walking next to the path to someone walking on the path who is not sick, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if it is unintentional;
if he is the first offender.
The twelfth training rule is finished.
Theravāda Collection on Monastic Law
The monks’ rules and their analysis
The chapter on training
The sub-chapter on laughing loudly
The training rule on laughing loudly
At one time the Buddha was staying at Sāvatthī in the Jeta Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s Monastery.
At that time the monks from the group of six were laughing loudly while walking in inhabited areas. …
“‘I will not laugh loudly while walking in inhabited areas,’ this is how you should train.”
One should not laugh loudly while walking in an inhabited area.
If a monk, out of disrespect, laughs loudly while walking in an inhabited area, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
if he does not know;
if he merely smiles when something is funny;
if he is insane;
if he is the first offender.
The first training rule is finished.
