A monk appoints someone to build him a hut and then departs.
He tells them to build a hut whose site has been approved, where no harm will be done, and which has a space on all sides,
but they build a hut whose site has not been approved, where harm will be done, and which lacks a space on all sides.
If he hears about it,
he must either go there himself or send a message,
and he must tell them to build a hut whose site has been approved, where no harm will be done, and which has a space on all sides.
If he neither goes himself nor sends a message, he commits an offense of wrong conduct.
